A '''frugal number''' is a [[natural number]] that has more [[numerical digit|digits]] than the number of digits in its [[prime factorization]] (including exponents).<ref name="Darling102">{{cite book |title=The universal book of mathematics: from Abracadabra to Zeno's paradoxes |last=Darling |first=David J. |year=2004 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |isbn=978-0-471-27047-8 |page=102 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nnpChqstvg0C&pg=PA102 }}</ref> For example, using base-10 arithmetic, the first few frugal numbers are 125 (5<sup>3</sup>), 128 (2<sup>7</sup>), 243 (3<sup>5</sup>), and 256 (2<sup>8</sup>). Frugal numbers also exist in other bases; for instance, in [[binary arithmetic]] thirty-two is a frugal number, since 10<sup>101</sup>&nbsp;=&nbsp;100000.
The base-10 frugal numbers up to 2000 are: :125, 128, 243, 256, 343, 512, 625, 729, 1024, 1029, 1215, 1250, 1280, 1331, 1369, 1458, 1536, 1681, 1701, 1715, 1792, 1849, 1875 {{OEIS|id=A046759}}
The term '''economical number''' has been used about a frugal number, but also about a number which is either frugal or [[Equidigital number|equidigital]].
== See also == *[[Equidigital number]] *[[Extravagant number]]
