{{Eastern name order|Hashiguchi Kosaburo}} {{Nihongo|'''Kosaburo Hashiguchi'''|橋口 攻三郎|Hashiguchi Kōsaburō}} is a Japanese mathematician and computer scientist at the [[Toyohashi University of Technology]] and [[Okayama University]], known for his research in [[formal language]] theory.
In 1988, he found the first [[algorithm]] to determine the [[star height]] of a [[regular language]], a problem that had been open since 1963 when Lawrence Eggan solved the related [[star height problem]] of showing that there is no finite bound on the star height. Hashiguchi's algorithm for star height is extremely complex, and impractical on all but the smallest examples.{{r|ls|pin}}{{ran|H88}} A simpler method, showing also that the problem is [[PSPACE-complete]], was provided in 2005 by Kirsten.{{r|ls|kirsten}}
Earlier, in 1979, Hashiguchi had also solved another open problem on regular languages, of deciding whether, for a given language <math>A</math>, there exists a finite number <math>n</math> such that <math>A^n=A^*</math>.{{r|brz}}{{ran|H79}}
Hashiguchi is the uncle of Japanese-born American pianist [[Grace Nikae]].{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}
